The Risk of Forcing Named Arguments Prematurely
If you attempt to write pre_flight_check(caller: "order_processor", ...) in an execution block today, you encounter a parsing bottleneck:

Grammar Inflation: Stage A's expression parser is optimized to tokenize functions as a direct identifier followed by a comma-separated list of values. Forcing named matching at call sites requires the tokenizer to anticipate optional parameter labels (Identifier ':' Expression) for every standard function invocation, complicating the core grammar before your syntax stabilizes.

AST Layer Mismatch: If the parser evaluates labels as standalone tokens, it has to map those tokens back to the target function's parameter registry during type-checking. If an automated code generation tool or human developer misorders the labels, the Stage A verifier could throw unhandled translation faults.

